3. Deployed Kafka using StatefulSet
Kafka needs stable identity + storage + ordering that why we use StatefulSet
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  a. Pod Identity (VERY IMPORTANT)
Your pods:
kafka-0
kafka-1
...
kafka-7
👉 These names NEVER change
👉 Each has DNS:
kafka-0.kafka-headless
kafka-1.kafka-headless
💡 Why needed?
Kafka brokers must:
Know each other
Communicate directly
👉 Without fixed names → cluster breaks
DNS = Domain Name System
👉 It converts names → IP addresses or IP addresses → names
Problem without DNS
Pods in Kubernetes get dynamic IPs
kafka-0 → 10.244.1.23 (today)
kafka-0 → 10.244.2.55 (after restart ❌
If Kafka uses IP:
Brokers cannot find each other
Cluster breaks ❌
Why DNS is used in your Kafka StatefulSet?
Your pods:
kafka-0
kafka-1
kafka-2
...
Each pod gets:
<pod-name>.<headless-service-name>
Example:
kafka-0.kafka-headless
kafka-1.kafka-headless
👉 This is stable DNS
How DNS solves it
Instead of IP, Kafka uses:
kafka-0.kafka-headless:9092
kafka-1.kafka-headless:9092
👉 Even if IP changes:
DNS updates automatically
Kafka still connects ✅
-----------------------------------------------------------
  b.Role of Headless Service
You used:
clusterIP: None
👉 This creates a Headless Service
👉 What it does:
Does NOT give a single IP
Gives DNS entry for each pod
So:
kafka-headless → multiple DNS records:
kafka-0.kafka-headless.default.svc.cluster.local
kafka-1.kafka-headless.default.svc.cluster.local
What is a Headless Service?
In Kubernetes, a Headless Service is created like this:
clusterIP: None
👉 That means:
No load balancing ❌
No single service IP ❌
Direct access to individual pods ✅
